{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_groomcreek_ver04/data/sn96060774/00414217618/1927010201/0245.xml":{"full_text":"WINOGALES INTERNATIONAL \"spf\nVol. 2.\u2014No. 31.\u20148 Pages\nLINE OR TWOJ\nOur Resolution for 1927\u2014T0\nsing the praises of Nogales, when\never and wherever the chance af\nfords; to tolerate no abuse and un\nfair criticism, and to help make\nNogales a bigger, brighter and bet\nter city. Will you join?\nHere is a sour note from Geor\nge Bernard Shaw, British dramat\nist, recently awarded the Nobel\nprize for literature, 1925, writing\nin the New Leader: \u201cIt has be\ncome an unbearable nuisance, but\nthe difficulty is to draft a bill\nmaking the celebration of Christ\nmas a criminal act, and compensat\ning the shopkeepers, who are just\n\u2014enabled by the Christmas trade to\npay their rents, not to mention all\nthe other people who make money\nout of it, and who do not know\nthat the landlords pocket it all In\nthe long run.\u201d Bernard must be i\nfeeling badly. 1\n\nJust before Christmas tL.- New 1\nhealth society of London issued\nthe following list of Christmas\nDont\u2019s: j\nDon\u2019t let the children stuff\nthemselves all day long with cand\nies. Dried fruits are much bet\nter for them. (Imagine the par\nents feeding their children dried\nfruits on Christmas.)\nDon\u2019t drink heavy vintage wines.\nThat advice is all right for London,\nnot needed in the United States.\nDon\u2019t indulge in cocktails. (Al\nso irrevalent, immaterial, and con\ntrary to the American statuatory\nprovisions.)\nDon\u2019t dance, or indulge In active\ngames until half an hour to an\nhour after dinner hour. East roast\nturkey, plum pudding and mince 1\npie and turn deaf ear for food\nfaddists.\n(Continued on Page 2.)\nIMPROVEMENTS AT\nINTERNATIONAL\nBUILDING 11\nExtensive improvements are un- 1\nder way at the Nogales Interna- i\ntional\u2019s building, 225 Grand ave-\nnue. The entire interior, both shop\nand office, are being painted, and\nwork of painting the front of the\n1 uilding, and remodeling the\nroof and interior, has just been\ncompleted.\nWhen all the repairs are com- i\npleted the structure will be one of\nthe most beautiful newspaper\nplants in Arizona in a city the\nsize of Nogales.\nIn addition to improvements The\nInternational is receiving each\nweek new equipment to add to its\nplant to expedite work of turn\ning out numerous orders for\nprinting.\nThe year 1926 was a banner\none for The International and the\nnew year starts off with indicat\nions for twice the volume of busi\nness that was done during the old\nyear.\nJisip\nGOOD YEAR FORECAST FOR NOGALES\nPaved Streets To Be Reality This Year 1\nALDERMAN BEAN\nMAKES REPORT\nON PAVING TO\n0. Os 0.\nPaved streets look like a reality\nduring the new year.\nAlderman R. C. \u00bbBean, at a\nmeeting of the Chamber of Com\nmerce Thursday night, made a re\nport on behalf of the mayor and\ncity council and explained the\nproblems to be overcome before\nwork of paving the streets gets\nactually under way.\nThe initial program calls for\nthe paving of Morley avenue to\nBanks Bridge, Grand avenue to\nthe city limits, and Court and\nPark streets. It was brought\nout that to pave these streets it\nwill be necessary for the South\nern Pacific railroad company to\npay about 34 percent of the cost\non account of so much railroad\nproperty \"being situated along the\nstreets.\nThe Chamber of Commerce, it\nit said, is solidly in favor of pav\ning but not strongly in favor of a\ngeneral bond issue. It seemed\nto be the concensus of opinion at\nthe meeting Thursday night that\neach property owner should pay\nhis cost himself and not put* the\nentire cost in a bond issue. It\nwas voted to name a committee to\ninterview the railroad company in\nregard to paving.\nPaving of the four above\nstreets and installation of orna\nmental street lights, it is under\nstood, will cost the railroad com\npany about SIOO,OOO, and other\nproperty owners approximately\n$200,000.\nAnnual Dinner Os\nChamber Commerce\nMayor John White of Tucson is\nexpected to be among out of town\nspeakers at the annual get-together\ndinner of the Chamber of Com\nmerce at 7 o\u2019clock Thursday ev\nening at the Firemen\u2019s Club.\nA very fine program is being\narranged and covers are expected\nto be laid for pi\u2019actically every\nbusiness man on the border.\nSecretary J. B. Bristol to\nmorrow will send out ballots to\nmembers of the chamber for\nelection of a board of thirty di\nrectors to serve during the year\n1927. The ballots will be de\nposited on the night of the din\nner.\nLocal People To\nMake World Tour\nMr. and Mrs. Dave Loeb are\nleaving Monday on a trip around\nthe world. They will be gone ten\nmonths and their first stop after\nleaving the United States will be\nat the Azore Islands.\nDaring their absence their beau\ntiful home on Marsh Heights will\nbe occupied by Mr. and Mrs. Joe\nBerk and daughter.\nMILLER CHAIRMAN\nNEW BOARD OF\nSUPERVISORS\nHugo W. Miller was named\nchairman of the board of super\nvisors for the next two years at\nthe organization meeting of the\nnew board Wednesday.\nMembers of the board, elected\nat the November election, and who\nbecame supervisors as the clock\nstruck midnight last night, are\nHugo W. Miller and Fred Hannah,\nrepublicans, both of Nogales, and\nWilliam T. Roath of Elgin, demo\ncrat.\nThe Board named A. Dumbauld\nclerk of the board. Mr. Dum\nbauld, democrat, has been the very\nefficient clerk the past four years.\nIt was voted that each supervis\nor continue to oversea the roads\nin his district.\nThe question of who will succeed\nDr. W. F. Chenoweth, democrat,\nas county physician, has not been\ndefinitely settled, it was stated\nFriday by Chairman Miller who ad\nded that the post would be offered\neo either Dr. V. A. Smelker or\nDr. A. L. Gustetter.\nThe new board favors a strict\nprogram of economy and one of\nthe first steps along this line was\nto vote to abolish the office of\ncourt interpreter, a position held\nuntil yesterday by Charles Lopez.\nFinal meeting of the retiring\nboard, made up of James L. Fin\nley of Car.ille, R. A. Campbell of\nPatagonia, and Hugo W. Miller of\nNogales, was held yesterday at\nwhich time they wound up the\nbusiness for the year.\nThe new board will hold it\u2019s first\nmeeting of the Tear on Monday.\nNogales, Arizona, Sunday January 2,1927\nGov. Hunt Signs\nNew Charter\ni\nGov. George W. F. Hunt has\nsigned the new city charter re\ncently drafted for this city by a\nboard of freeholders, it was an\nnounced at the meeting of the\nChamber of Commerce Thursday\nnight.\nThe charter now goes to the\nmayor and city council for sign\nature, after which it will be re\ncorded and soon become effect\nive.\nMast Hare Paving\nTo Become First\nClass City\nNogales can never become a\nfirst class city until paved streets\nare laid here.\nThis is the opinion of Bracey\nCurtis, president of the First Nat\nional Bank, in a statement made\nWednesday to the Nogales Inter\nnational.\n\u201cNogales will never be a first\nclass.city until we get paving, and\nwith paving we\u2019ll save money over\nour present antequated method.\nMorley avenue, Grand avenue,\nand some of the streets over the\nhills should be paved\u201d said Mr.\nCurtis. i I 0 t\n\u201cThe only thing the taxpayers\ninsist on is that paving shall be\nput down under expert paving en\ngineers\u2019 advice, and that the\ndrainage from Mexico be handled\nin an intelligent way and that we\nreceive aa near one dollar worth\nNEW YEAR BRINGS\nNEW SET OF CO.\nOFFICIALS\nWith the opening q! the new\nyear today, Santa Cruz County\nnas a new set of officials who\nwere elected in November and be\ncame office holders as the clock\nstruck midnight last night.\nCounty officials elected to serve\nfor two years beginning today are\nW. A. O\u2019Connor, judge of the\nsuperior court; Bonsall Noon,\ncounty attorney; Robert E. Lee,\nclerk of the superior court; Mrs.\nAnna B. Ackley, treasurer; Mrs.\nAda Jones, recorder; Harry V.\nFarrior, assessor; Harold Brown,\nsheriff; Mrs. Grace Farrell, school\nsuperintendent; and Hugo W.\nMiller, Fred Hannah, and William\nT. Roath, members of the board\nI of supervisors.\nOs the above list, O\u2019Connor,\nLee, Mrs. Ackley, Brown, Mrs.\nFarrell, and Mailer, served during\nthe two years prior to today. Noon\nsucceeds James V. Robins, Mrs.\nJones succeeds Tracy Bird, and\nHanah and Roath succeed Robert\nA. Campbell and James L. Finley\non the board of supervisors.\nCounty Attorney Noon has nam\ned Miss Alice Johnson as his clerk,\nMiss Carmen O'Neill is deputy to\nMrs. Jones, Mrs. Frank Lynch\ndeputy to Assessor Farrior, Agnes\nG. Hamlin deputy to Mrs. Ackley,\nand Miss Viola Allen deputy to\nRobert E. Lee. A. Dumbauld\ncontinues as clerk of the board of\nsupervisors.\nof paving for every dollar put up\nby the taxpayers aa any town or\ncity this sise should hops to gat.**\nBIG YEAR PREDICTED:\nFOR CITY OF NOGALES'\nDY PROMINENT MEK\nThe new year starts off with\nevery indication of 1927 being the\ngreatest period in the history gs\nNogales.\nThe Nogales International ob\ntained statements from several\nprominent business men on the\noutlook for 1927. Read what they\nhave to say.\nR. C. Bean, member of the\nboard aldermen president of the\nNogales Rotary club, and manager\nof the Nogales office of the Inter\nnational Commission Company,\nsays: \u201cI am a firm believer in\nthe future of Nogales. I hope\nthat it will be possible to pave our\nstreets during 1927, then we will\nhave something to advertise. Good\npaving will bring new people and\nnew homes and greater prosperity\nfor Nogales.\u201d\nDave Loeb, retired capitalist,\n6tates: \u201cThe people of Nogales\nhave the making of a wonderful\ncity. Climatic conditions are\nsuch as to appeal to all eastern\npeople who are not so fortune.\nThe geographical position of No\ngales and the business outlook,\nconsidering the completion in Feb\nruary of the Nogales-Mexico City\nrailroad, should make Nogales with\nthe assistance of fta citizens, a\nsecond El Paso.\u201d\nBRACEY CURTIS\nBracey Curtis, president of the\nFirst National Bank, says: I\nthink the prospects for 1927 are\nexcellent. The year 1926 was\nPOPPER-ROASTER\nLEFT BY SANTA\nSanta Claus left a beautiful\npopper and roaster at E. L.\nChalfant\u2019s confectionery store\non Grand avenue, two doors north\nof the office of the Ngales Inter\nnationaL\nThis machine, the best on the\nmarket, and purchased at a high,\nyet reasonable cost, is attracting\nmuch attention from Chalfant\u2019s\nmany customers.\nIt has double the pop corn and\npeanut capacity of other makes\nwhich sell for twice its size. It\nmakes the most delicious pop com\nobtainable, the tempting butter\nflavor being cooked right into the\nheart of every fluffy morsel\u2014\neach grain being seasoned precise\nly alike. Butter an\u00a3 salt flavor\ngoes right into each porous cell!'\nNo greasy bags or fingers\u2014is an\nother reason why the children and\ngrown-ups appreciate its pro\nduct.\nThe machine, manufactured by\nC. Cretors A Company of Chica\ngo, has a pop com output of 140\nto 160 one pound bags\u2014or 175 to\n200 three-quarter pound size bags\nper hour, and 'its peanut roasting\ncapacity is B 0 five-cent sacks ev\nery 80 minutes, or 100 bags per\n{hour.\n5 Cents a Copy\nvery good with the exception of th\nrailroad washouts which made it\npretty bad in a retail way. With\nthe general prospects even\nin a normal way than they were l1\n1926 and big crops coming\nj west coast of Mexico, it looks like\"\na very prosperous year ahead lit\u2019**'\nthis time, with the addition of thtf'?\nnew main line railroad of v -tlWf\nSouthern Pacific de Mexico- cbiSt- 1 v\nnecting up Nogales with the\nior of Mexico and putting Noga\nles on the main line between ShiK\nFrancisco and Mexico City. 'Tbis \u2018*2*>\nis all bound to make 1927' a Veiy,\nprosperous year for both\nArizona, and Nogales, Sonora.\nIn addition to my opinion of .the-;;\nprosperity of Mexico, comes thefy;\nunusual activity in mining ip the\nPatagonia and Oro Banco dis\ntricts, also the agricultural out-;f;\nlook in the Calabasas district foil?-\nlettuce and other vegetables isj|*\nvery good. With the unusual\nand health development coming;\nfrom our Mexican trade\nand from Santa Cruz county,\nbelieve that Nogales will enjoy 7\nmore prosperity the coming year:r\nthan it has ever enjoyed before.,\nin its history.\u201d fc\nMAX MULLER\n\u201cThe outlook for 1927 is very|i\ngood for Nogales.\u201d it was\ned by Max Muller,\nof the Sonora Bank Trust\npany. \u201cBusiness from the\ncoast of Mexico is increasing ev->\nery day as far as exports and im\u00a3\nports are concerned, of which No\ngales gets it's good share.\nexpectation that railroad connect,\ntions will be made in March or?\nApril, with Guadalajara, is makjg\ning local business men atjd\nty owners very optimistic,,and wjeij\nwill undoubtedly see a great in\ncrease in population and business*\nin general in Ambos Nogales. AJi\ngood many people are hopeful of;\nseeing several new industries es 4\ntablished on the American side of\nthe line as soon as the railroad is\nopened.\u201d jg\nA. G. STEARNS M\nA. G. Stearns, manager* of H.\nMexico-Arizona Trading Compa\nny. says:\u2014\u201cThere has been\nsaid about tbe future prosperity\nof Nogales and that\nwould pick up rapridly when rail\nroad connection was made with thj\u00bb\n(Continued on Page 7) jv\nI\ns\nOur BestWisixes\nJixA IfearofEoui\\ty 1 fearofEoui\\ty","height":"26853","width":"18798"}}
